// @check
// @error-at 10:9 Type `E` refers to itself inside an intersection (`A & E`), so it reduces to `never`
// A self-referential intersection `type E = A & E` is NONSENSE — `E` is defined
// in terms of itself, so it collapses to `never`. It gets an honest, self-cycle
// message ("refers to itself inside an intersection … reduces to `never`"), NOT
// the disjoint-operands wording and NOT the old confusing "a number literal and
// a type" (PR #189 review). The diagnostic RANGE lands on the `A & E`
// intersection EXPRESSION (0-indexed `10:9`, the `type E = A & E` annotation),
// not the alias name or the value site.
type A = { a: string }
type E = A & E
let e: E = { a: "x" }
print(e)
